Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 450 degrees. Wash and dry
produce.

Peel and mince @ginger{1%thumb} until you have 1 TBSP (2 TBSP for 4 servings). Cut
@broccoli florets{8%ounce} into bite-size pieces if necessary. Peel and mince or grate @garlic{1%clove}. Zest and quarter @lime{1}.

== Ginger Lime Rice ==

Melt 1 TBSP @butter{2%tablespoon} in a #small pot{} over medium-high heat.
Add half the minced ginger (you'll use the rest later); cook, stirring, until
softened, ~{1%minute}.

Stir in @jasmine rice{1/2%cup}, 3/4 cup water (1 1/2 cups for 4),
and a big pinch of @salt{}. Bring to a boil, then cover and reduce to a low simmer.
Cook until rice is tender, ~{15-18%minutes}.

Keep covered off heat until ready to serve.

== Roasted Broccoli ==

While rice cooks, toss broccoli on a #baking sheet{} with a drizzle of @cooking oil{}, @salt{}, and @pepper{}.

Roast on top rack until browned and tender, ~{12-15%minutes}.

== Apricot Ponzu Chicken ==

While broccoli roasts, pat @chicken cutlets{10%ounce} dry with paper towels. Season all over with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add chicken and
cook until browned and cooked through, ~{3-5%minutes} per side.

Transfer to a #cutting board{}. Remove pan from heat to cool slightly.

Return pan used for chicken to medium heat. Add a drizzle of @cooking oil{},
garlic, and remaining minced ginger; cook, stirring, until fragrant, ~{30%seconds}.

Add @apricot jam{1}, @ponzu sauce{18%milliliters}, and 1/4 cup water (1/3 cup for 4 servings). Stir, scraping
up any browned bits from bottom of pan, until combined and thickened,
~{3-4%minutes}.

Remove pan from heat; stir in @butter{} and a squeeze of lime juice to taste.

Fluff rice with a #fork{}; stir in as much lime zest as you like. Season with @salt{} to taste.

Slice chicken crosswise.

Divide rice, chicken, and broccoli between #plates{}. Drizzle pan sauce over
chicken. Serve with any remaining lime wedges on the side.

> Chicken is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 165°.

> Those sides would be equally delicious with the sauce. This is one full meal we're pretty sure you'll want to whip up around the cluck.